bug.short_desc: HTML Editor disagrees with syntax generated by Sun Javadoc

long_desc.thetext:
Version: 3.3.1.1 Build id: M20071023-1652
This is interesting ... I ran javadoc over all our classes. Immediately Eclipse error window blew up with thousands of errors. But, you know what? They were not java source files error. Eclipse was whining about the syntax of the HTML generated by javadoc tool. As far as I can see, the html in the generated javadoc has no problems.
This problem has been appearing in Eclipse 3.2 also.
Created attachment 86711 Eclipse HTML Editor whining about "misplaced" NOSCRIPT tag
Created attachment 86712 Eclipse HTML Editor whining about unstarted BLOCKQUOTE end-tag
Does eclipse disagree with Sun javadoc over HTML syntax standards?
Please attach a complete HTML file so I can double-check it. What does the W3C validator say?

Created attachment 86942 Eclipse workspace with single project
Attach is a zip which contains a single JEE project. I am uploading it ONCE for both this bug and 183302.
In the project is a class big.fat.rat.RedHatRat which is located in src/big/fat/rat/RedHatRat.java. There is doc folder generated by javadoc. The javadoc is generated using Eclipse javadoc wizard over the src folder.s Eclipse problem pane will show two sets of errors: 1. Error in html in the javadoc. 2. Error in html of FixedBrownHogHumpsOverSkinnyDog.jsp simply because "post" in method="POST" is in uppercase.
You will find that the FixedBrownHogHumpsOverSkinnyDog.jsp will run on Tomcat without error to generate a blank page on the browser.

Created attachment 86943 Eclipse workspace with single project
Attach is a zip which contains a single JEE project. I am uploading it ONCE for both this bug and 183302.
In the project is a class big.fat.rat.RedHatRat which is located in src/big/fat/rat/RedHatRat.java. There is doc folder generated by javadoc. The javadoc is generated using Eclipse javadoc wizard over the src folder.s Eclipse problem pane will show two sets of errors: 1. Error in html in the javadoc. 2. Error in html of FixedBrownHogHumpsOverSkinnyDog.jsp simply because "post" in method="POST" is in uppercase.
You will find that the FixedBrownHogHumpsOverSkinnyDog.jsp will run on Tomcat without error to generate a blank page on the browser.

This is still reproducible in WTP 3.2 but running the doc file through the W3 validator one of the error messages is:
Line 69, Column 10: document type does not allow element "NOSCRIPT" here; missing one of "APPLET", "OBJECT", "MAP", "IFRAME", "BUTTON" start-tag
<NOSCRIPT>
Thus I would say our validation is in the right here and there is not much we can do about the javadoc generating invalid markup. Vote to resolve.

We try to stick as close as possible to standards validation. So, while a lot of things may happen to work in browsers, we'd like to be consistent. This is the reason you're noticing a lot of warnings in your html files.
For the JSP file, it is xhtml, where case matters. So it must be post and not POST. Again, this is a case of browsers being flexible.
